{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"fields":{"description":"# Live-store remediation: drive fsck to zero (safe, reversible, batched, committed)\n\n## Why\n`rebar fsck` on the live store = 2422 SNAPSHOT_INCONSISTENT + 11 ORPHAN_EVENT + 1 MISSING_CREATE. Fix #1\nstopped new corruption; this cleans the backlog. DESTRUCTIVE on a live, git-backed shared store — safety is\nfirst-class. Sibling deliverables are NEW work: A1 (tricolour-head-ratfish) ADDS the `.retired` rename +\n`RETIRED_SUFFIX`; A2 (glandulous-potent-waxwing) ADDS the `include_retired` rebuild path. depends_on A1+A2.\n\n## Repair per fault class\n- SNAPSHOT_INCONSISTENT (2422): a folded source file STILL PRESENT (listed in `source_event_uuids`, never\n  deleted). Repair = retire (`.retired`) each still-present listed source. The retire helper is invoked from the\n  `fsck --repair` path (shared with A1's rename logic). NOT a rebuild.\n- ORPHAN_EVENT (11): a pre-snapshot event absent from `source_event_uuids` -> A2's `reduce_ticket(..., include_retired=True)` rebuild -> re-write snapshot.\n- MISSING_CREATE (1): `fsck --repair` logs it and routes to human triage (no automatic write).\n\n## Safety\n- GIT-AWARE writes: the tracker is a git worktree. Each batch of per-ticket repairs is committed+pushed:\n  `git -C <tracker> add -A && git -C <tracker> commit -m 'a3-remediation: batch N/M' && git -C <tracker> push`.\n  The pre-remediation restore point and rollback are git-level and cover these commits: BEFORE any write,\n  `git -C <tracker> tag pre-a3-remediation <oid>`; rollback = `git -C <tracker> reset --hard pre-a3-remediation\n  && git -C <tracker> push --force-with-lease`.\n- Dry-run FIRST: `fsck --repair --dry-run` prints per-ticket before/after diff + dispositions, writes NOTHING\n  (a test asserts the dry-run makes zero file writes and zero commits); the live run is gated on human review.\n- Reconciler pause (real mechanism; `OBSERVE` is NOT a Mode): disable the `reconcile-bridge.yml` GHA schedule for\n  the window (primary) — the pass-lock `refs/reconciler/lock` is a leased CAS lock (ADR 0031) and would expire, so\n  it is NOT the pause mechanism. Verify no pass is mid-flight before starting; re-enable the schedule after. Manual\n  writers hold off during the window (documented); because enforcement is social, the batched+committed design\n  means a stray concurrent write merges rather than being lost, and the pre-tag enables rollback.\n- Idempotent/resumable: the AUTHORITATIVE resumability check is fsck itself (re-run repairs only tickets fsck still\n  flags). A per-ticket `.a3-repaired` marker is a LOCAL, gitignored optimization only (never committed) so a git\n  rollback need not track it; a stale marker after rollback is harmless (fsck re-derives). A crash between the\n  snapshot rename and the marker write is safe (fsck re-checks). Per-snapshot replace is atomic (write `<snap>.tmp`,\n  `os.rename` over old); per-ticket failure logs+skips (no batch abort). Batched `--limit=200`, wait >=30s between.\n\n## Orphan disposition policy\n- AUTO-RECOVER (additive): COMMENT, LINK, UNLINK, TAG_DELTA, COMMITS.\n- HUMAN TRIAGE (LWW-scalar; order unrecoverable): STATUS, EDIT (title/description/priority/assignee/parent),\n  FILE_IMPACT, VERIFY_COMMANDS, SIGNATURE (the top-level signature mirror). Decision recorded in the PR / ops doc.\n\n## Scope\n`_commands/fsck.py` (`--repair`/`--dry-run`/`--limit` + per-batch git commit + local marker + atomic per-snapshot\nrewrite + retire-still-present), `_commands/compact.py` (shared retire helper). Consumes A1's `.retired` + A2's\n`include_retired`. Gated on RC1 fix #1 (deployed).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `fsck --repair --dry-run` prints per-ticket before/after + dispositions; a test asserts ZERO file writes and ZERO git commits in dry-run.\n- [ ] Live repair commits+pushes each batch to the tickets branch; pre-remediation tag created; rollback (`reset --hard` + `--force-with-lease`) documented AND rehearsed on a fixture (asserts post-rollback store == pre-tag state).\n- [ ] Reconciler paused by disabling the GHA schedule (verified no in-flight pass); re-enabled after.\n- [ ] Resumability authoritative via fsck re-check; `.a3-repaired` marker is local/gitignored; a test verifies a re-run skips already-clean tickets and that a crash-before-marker is safe.\n- [ ] Synthetic-fixture unit tests: known SNAPSHOT_INCONSISTENT / ORPHAN_EVENT / MISSING_CREATE (incl. `.retired`) repair correctly; per-snapshot replace is atomic.\n- [ ] Live store reaches 0 UNRESOLVED faults (triaged+documented orphans count as resolved); before/after counts recorded.\n\n\n## Round-5 refinements (from plan review)\n- ATOMIC WRITE: the per-snapshot rewrite uses the EXISTING `rebar._store.fsutil.atomic_write` (as compact.py/txn.py\n  do) — do not hand-roll tmp+rename.\n- HELPER OWNERSHIP: the retire-still-present logic lives in the `fsck --repair` path (reusing A1's\n  `RETIRED_SUFFIX`/rename); A1 (tricolour-head-ratfish) owns all `compact.py` changes, so this ticket does NOT edit\n  `compact.py` (removed from Scope) — it calls A1's helper.\n- ORPHAN TRIAGE vs REBUILD: an ORPHAN_EVENT whose orphaned event is an AUTO-RECOVER additive type is rebuilt; one\n  whose orphaned event is a HUMAN-TRIAGE LWW-scalar type is NOT auto-rebuilt — it is surfaced to triage (the rebuild\n  would pick an order that may be wrong). fsck --repair routes by event type accordingly.\n- CLI GOLDEN: update the `fsck --help` golden files (`tests/golden/cli_help/fsck__help.out` + the `-h` variant) for the new `--repair`/`--dry-run`/`--limit` flags.\n- The rollback procedure + reconciler-pause steps + orphan disposition policy are captured in the PR description / a linked ops doc (not only plan prose).\n"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783479643354203001,"uuid":"8e230be4-0180-4ca9-8e1d-348dd5dab9b0"}